  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "One possible difference is that the kind of cognitive agency involved in offloading -but, possibly not in purely internal cognition -is under intentional control.",
    "It has been argued that a process's being under intentional control marks it out as non-cognitive.",
    "For instance, Galen Strawson (2003) has claimed that all genuine cognition is \"passive\", noting that one cannot decide to, for example, draw an inference or make a judgment in the same way as one decides to tie one's shoelaces.",
    "If this is the case, then putatively extended cognitive actions can be excluded on principle.",
    "Strawson's position, however, lies one end of a spectrum that, at its other extreme, encompasses claims that there no stable distinction to be drawn between mental and bodily actions -both of which might be intentional in the relevant sense (see, e.g., Levy, 2019)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
